Dear Corjan,

One of my activities is the development of the "Crop insurance based on soil moisture index" service, which according to the document I have (attached) relies on data which the FutureWater team will collect as part of WP4.2.

Following the WP4 Skype meeting a few weeks ago there were a few things I wasn't quite clear about, and I wondered if you would be able to shed some light. Firstly regarding the DTS campaign:

1. What will be the spatial coverage of the DTS that will be installed at the pilot locations?
2. In the vertical direction, will the sensor give a single measurement (i.e. for one depth) or a distribution?
3. The soil moisture index service will just be a prototype, but clearly if it is ever to move beyond a prototype there would need to be a way to collect soil moisture data at the regional level - which I guess is where the satellite data comes in. Is the intention that high-res DTS data can be used to downscale the satellite data (and is this something you're planning to work on)?

I also had a couple of questions about the UAV work:
4. Please could you share a list of variables that the UAVs will measure? The proposal mentions "greenness, canopy temperature and cover fraction, and crop dryness status", but it would be really helpful to have a list so that I can relate them to variables simulated by crop models (typically LAI).
5. What will be the legacy of the UAV work? For example, is the idea that the TWIGA countries will use UAVs operationally to monitor crop health, or will the data collected by UAVs during TWIGA be used to infer relationships with which to downscale satellite data?





